{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a0c094d6c89e34e6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tH-SAGE: Holistic Speaker-Aware Guided Experts\n2\tfor MoE-based Multi-Talker ASR\n3\tYujie Guo1 , Jiaming Zhou1 , Yuhang Jia1 , Yang Chen1 , and Yong Qin1,∗\n4\t1\n5\t\n6\tarXiv:2607.01566v1 [cs.SD] 2 Jul 2026\n7\t\n8\tTMCC, College of Computer Science, Nankai University, Tianjin, China\n9\t{guoyujie02,zhoujiaming,2120240729,2120230617}@mail.nankai.edu.cn, qinyong@nankai.edu.cn\n10\t\n11\tAbstract—Multi-talker\n12\tAutomatic\n13\tSpeech\n14\tRecognition\n15\t(MTASR) faces significant challenges in accurately transcribing\n16\toverlapping speech, particularly under complex high-overlap\n17\tconditions. While recent Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) approaches\n18\thave shown promise, they typically rely on frame-independent\n19\trouting that leads to temporal myopia, and depend solely on\n20\tthe downstream ASR objective, which results in implicit and\n21\tungrounded representation learning. To address these limitations,\n22\twe propose Holistic Speaker-Aware Guided Experts (H-SAGE)\n23\tfor MoE-based MTASR. Specifically, we introduce a SpeakerAware Global Encoder to capture long-term dependencies,\n24\tsupervised by an auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss that explicitly\n25\tguides the model to discern acoustic states. Furthermore,\n26\twe design a Holistic Gating Mechanism to arbitrate expert\n27\tselection by jointly evaluating global context and local details.\n28\tExperiments on LibriSpeechMix demonstrate that H-SAGE\n29\tachieves consistent improvements over strong baselines,\n30\tparticularly in complex scenarios, validating that explicit\n31\tacoustic guidance effectively enhances expert collaboration. Our\n32\tcode can be found at https://github.com/NKU-HLT/H-SAGE.\n33\tIndex Terms—multi-talker automatic speech recognition, cocktail party problem, Mixture-of-Experts, speaker-aware\n34\t\n35\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n36\tIn recent years, Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) has\n37\twitnessed remarkable progress due to the advent of deep\n38\tlearning. State-of-the-art architectures have achieved humanlevel performance in clean, single-speaker scenarios. However,\n39\tthese systems often degrade significantly in realistic conversational environments, which are characterized by spontaneous\n40\tturn-taking and frequent speech overlaps. This limitation has\n41\tcatalyzed the emergence of Multi-Talker ASR (MTASR) as\n42\ta critical research frontier. Unlike traditional ASR, which\n43\tassumes a monotonic mapping between a single acoustic\n44\tstream and text, MTASR aims to simultaneously disentangle\n45\tand transcribe overlapping utterances from multiple speakers,\n46\taddressing the classic “Cocktail Party Problem”.\n47\tCurrent end-to-end MTASR approaches fall into two\n48\tparadigms: Single-Input Multiple-Output (SIMO) and SingleInput Single-Output (SISO) [1]. SIMO-based methods [2]–\n49\t[4] utilize Permutation Invariant Training (PIT) [5] to assign\n50\tspeech to specific branches. While effective, they are constrained by a fixed number of output branches, limiting their\n51\tflexibility when the speaker count is unknown or variable.\n52\tIn contrast, SISO approaches employ Serialized Output\n53\tTraining (SOT) [6] to generate a serialized transcription con∗ Corresponding author. This work was supported by the National Natural\n54\tScience Foundation of China (62271270).\n55\t\n56\ttaining all speakers. This paradigm inherently handles variable\n57\tspeaker counts, offering superior flexibility. However, it relies\n58\theavily on the attention mechanism to implicitly disentangle\n59\toverlapping speech. Without explicit guidance, the model often\n60\tstruggles to distinguish speakers in high-overlap segments,\n61\tresulting in performance degradation.\n62\tTo mitigate this issue, recent research has pivoted towards\n63\taugmenting SISO frameworks with explicit speaker modeling,\n64\tutilizing auxiliary modules or objectives to capture discriminative speaker characteristics. For instance, CSE-SOT [7]\n65\temploys multi-branch structures to capture distinct speaker\n66\trepresentation. Similarly, SACTC [8] and SD-CTC [9] leverage improved connectionist temporal classification to explicitly guide the encoders in separating speaker information.\n67\tFurthermore, SSA [10] utilizes an external diarization system\n68\tto explicitly provide speaker activity cues, guiding the ASR\n69\tmodel to generate speaker-specific transcriptions.\n70\tParallel to these advancements, the Mixture-of-Experts\n71\t(MoE) paradigm has recently been explored in MTASR, with\n72\tGLAD [11] representing an early attempt. Despite integrating\n73\tglobal and local routers, GLAD suffers from key structural\n74\tlimitations. Its global information relies on frame-independent\n75\tprojections, preventing effective modeling of speaker-level\n76\ttemporal dynamics. Moreover, its speaker-aware behavior is\n77\tlearned only implicitly through the standard ASR training\n78\tobjective, making the router prone to shortcut learning rather\n79\tthan acquiring robust discriminative cues. Finally, its expert\n80\tselection strategy is derived solely from local representations,\n81\tgiving the router a narrow, non-holistic perspective that limits\n82\tits adaptability to complex acoustic conditions.\n83\tTo address these issues, we propose Holistic SpeakerAware Guided Experts (H-SAGE), a framework that rethinks\n84\texpert routing for MoE-based MTASR. H-SAGE comprises\n85\ttwo complementary components: a Speaker-Aware Global\n86\tEncoder (SA-Encoder) that explicitly models speaker activity\n87\tstates—such as silence, single-speaker, and overlap—guided\n88\tby an auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ), and a Holistic\n89\tGating Mechanism that assigns experts by jointly leveraging\n90\tglobal acoustic context and local frame-level cues. Together,\n91\tthese components deliver more reliable and context-informed\n92\trouting decisions, addressing the core limitations of prior\n93\tMoE-based approaches. Our contributions are as follows:\n94\t• We propose H-SAGE, a novel framework anchored by a\n95\tSA-Encoder. Supervised by an auxiliary Overlap-Aware\n96\tLoss, this design captures evolving acoustic states and\n97\t\n98\t\f𝓛ASR\n99\t\n100\t𝓛OA\n101\tTarget\n102\tOA-Sequence\n103\t\n104\tCompute\n105\tLoss\n106\t\n107\tCompute\n108\tLoss\n109\t\n110\tGround\n111\tTruth\n112\t\n113\tPredict Transcription\n114\tOA-Sequence\n115\t\n116\t𝑷𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n117\t\n118\t𝑶𝒖𝒕\n119\t\n120\t𝑿𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n121\t\n122\t+\n123\tGlobal\n124\tRouter\n125\t\n126\tWeighted\n127\tSum\n128\t\n129\t𝑷\n130\t\n131\tTransformer\n132\tDecoder\n133\t\n134\t+\n135\t\n136\t𝑷𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n137\t\n138\t\n139\t\n140\t+\n141\t\n142\t\n143\t\n144\tLinear\n145\t\n146\t𝑷𝒍𝒐𝒄𝒂𝒍\n147\t\n148\tFeed Forward\n149\t\n150\t𝑿𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n151\t\n152\tConformer\n153\tEncoder\n154\t\n155\tSA-Encoder\n156\t\n157\tLinear\n158\t\n159\t+\n160\t\n161\t𝑷𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n162\t\n163\tMulti-Head\n164\tSelf Attention\n165\t\n166\tSA-Encoder\n167\t\n168\tSA-Encoder\n169\t\n170\t𝑿𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n171\t\n172\tLocal\n173\tRouter\n174\t\n175\t𝑩𝟏\n176\t\n177\t𝑩𝟐\n178\t\n179\t𝑨𝟏\n180\t\n181\t𝑨𝟐\n182\t\n183\t𝑩𝑵\n184\t\n185\t…\n186\t𝑨𝑵\n187\t\n188\tShared\n189\tLinear\n190\t\n191\tc\n192\t\n193\tHolistic Gating\n194\tA MoLE Layer in Conformer\n195\t\n196\t𝑿𝒔𝒑𝒆𝒆𝒄𝒉\n197\t\n198\t𝑿𝒔𝒑𝒆𝒆𝒄𝒉\n199\t(a) Training of H-SAGE\n200\t\n201\t(b) Structure of SA-Encoder\n202\t\n203\t𝑿𝒔𝒑𝒆𝒆𝒄𝒉\n204\t\n205\t𝑿𝒍𝒐𝒄𝒂𝒍\n206\t(c) MoLE with Holistic Gating used in H-SAGE\n207\t\n208\tFig. 1: Overview of the H-SAGE architecture. (a) Training Pipeline: The Conformer Encoder integrates the MoLE blocks shown\n209\tin (c). The model is jointly optimized by LASR and the explicit Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ). (b) Structure of SA-Encoder:\n210\tSA-Encoder extracts global context from the convolutional frontend output Xspeech , producing global routing probabilities\n211\tPglobal and context features Xglobal . (c) MoLE used in H-SAGE: Detailed structure of the MoLE block. These blocks replace\n212\tall the linear transformations in the Conformer Encoder. The Holistic Gating mechanism fuses global context (Xglobal ) and\n213\tlocal input (Xlocal ) to adaptively balance routing probabilities for precise expert selection.\n214\tshifts the routing paradigm from implicit representation\n215\tlearning to explicit acoustic modeling.\n216\t• We introduce a Holistic Gating Mechanism to optimize\n217\texpert assignment. By synthesizing global acoustic contexts with local representations, it ensures a comprehensive perspective for robust expert selection.\n218\t• Experiments on LibriSpeechMix demonstrate consistent\n219\timprovements over strong baselines in multi-talker scenarios. Crucially, further analysis validates the effectiveness of the proposed mechanisms, confirming their role in\n220\texpert collaboration and robust speaker disentanglement.\n221\tII. P RELIMINARY K NOWLEDGE\n222\tA. Serialized Output Training\n223\tSerialized Output Training (SOT) [6] serves as a prominent\n224\tSingle-Input Single-Output (SISO) paradigm in MTASR. In\n225\tcontrast to architectures relying on multiple output branches,\n226\tSOT leverages a single decoder to transcribe overlapping\n227\tspeech from a variable number of speakers into a unified\n228\tsequence. Given an utterance with N speakers, the model\n229\tis trained to generate a concatenated sequence formatted as\n230\tY = {text1 , ⟨sc⟩, text2 , . . . , ⟨sc⟩, textN }, where texti represents the transcription sequence of the i-th speaker, and ⟨sc⟩\n231\tdenotes a special speaker-change token. We adopt the FirstIn, First-Out (FIFO) strategy, organizing transcripts chronologically based on speaker onset. This serialization strategy\n232\tallows the model to implicitly disentangle overlapping speech,\n233\teffectively bypassing the combinatorial complexity associated\n234\twith permutation-based methods.\n235\tB. MoE-based MTASR\n236\tGLAD [11] represents a pioneering effort in applying the\n237\tMixture-of-Low-Rank-Experts (MoLE) paradigm to MTASR.\n238\tIt replaces all linear layers within the encoder with MoLE\n239\t\n240\tblocks, whose structure resembles MoE-LoRA [12]. Given an\n241\tinput feature X ∈ Rdin , the output is formulated as:\n242\tα PN\n243\tY = WX +\n244\tPi Bi Ai X + b,\n245\t(1)\n246\tr i=1\n247\twhere W and b denote the weights and bias of the shared\n248\tlinear layer, respectively. Adopting the structural design of\n249\tLoRA [13], each Low-Rank expert is parameterized by lowrank matrices Ai ∈ Rr×din and Bi ∈ Rdout ×r with rank\n250\tr ≪ min(din , dout ), scaled by a factor α. The expert weight\n251\tPi is computed via a gating mechanism that combines global\n252\tand local routing signals.\n253\tThe expert activation weight Pi is computed via a gating\n254\tmechanism that combines global and local routing signals.\n255\tSpecifically, GLAD employs a linear projection on the convolutional frontend output to derive a frame-independent global\n256\trouter, while the local router is derived from the current\n257\tlayer’s hidden states. The fusion coefficient is derived from the\n258\tcurrent layer’s features to balance these signals. Consequently,\n259\tthe final routing weight fuses the frame-independent global\n260\tprojection with instantaneous local representations.\n261\tIII. O UR M ETHODS\n262\tAs illustrated in Fig. 1 (a), H-SAGE is built upon an MoEbased encoder-decoder architecture. Consistent with prior\n263\twork [11], we replace standard linear layers in the encoder\n264\twith MoLE blocks. Uniquely, our architecture integrates two\n265\tkey modules: the SA-Encoder module (Fig. 1 (b)), which\n266\tcaptures global acoustic context supervised by the OverlapAware Loss, and the Holistic Gating Mechanism (Fig. 1\n267\t(c)), which synthesizes global acoustic contexts with local\n268\trepresentations for expert routing.\n269\tA. Speaker-Aware Global Encoder with Explicit Supervision\n270\tTo transition from implicit adaptation to explicit acoustic modeling, we introduce SA-Encoder. Unlike frame-\n271\t\n272\t\fSpeaker2\n273\t\n274\tSpeaker1\n275\t\n276\tMixed wave\n277\t\n278\tTarget overlap-aware\n279\tsequence\n280\t\n281\t𝐓3\n282\t\n283\t𝐓2\n284\t\n285\t𝐓𝟏\n286\t\n287\t𝐓4\n288\t\n289\tT : number of frames\n290\t0 : padding frames\n291\t1 : frames where only one speaker is\n292\tactive\n293\t2 : frames containing overlapping\n294\tspeech from multiple speakers\n295\t\n296\tLoss LOA is then computed as the Cross-Entropy between\n297\tthe predictions and the targets Yoverlap aware . Minimizing\n298\tthis objective explicitly supervises the model to distinguish\n299\tbetween single-talker and multi-talker segments, providing\n300\trobust guidance for expert selection.\n301\t\n302\t[𝟏. . . 𝟏, 2. . . 2, 𝟏. . . 𝟏, 𝟎. . . 𝟎]\n303\t𝐓𝟏\n304\t\n305\t𝐓2\n306\t\n307\t𝐓3\n308\t\n309\t𝐓4\n310\t\n311\t𝓛 OA (Compute loss using Cross-entropy loss)\n312\t\n313\tPredicted overlap-aware sequence\n314\t\n315\tFig. 2: The detail of Overlap-Aware Loss\n316\tindependent projections that suffer from temporal myopia, SAEncoder is designed to capture dynamic speaker activity states\n317\tvia long-term dependency modeling, explicitly supervised by\n318\tan auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ).\n319\tSA-Encoder: As illustrated in Fig. 1 (b), SA-Encoder operates directly on the signals Xspeech ∈ RT ×D extracted by the\n320\tconvolutional frontend. This design effectively preserves rich\n321\tacoustic characteristics that are often diluted in deeper network\n322\tlayers. Deviating from simple linear projection, SA-Encoder\n323\tincorporates a Multi-Head Self-Attention block followed by a\n324\tFeed-Forward Network. This architecture enables the model to\n325\tcapture long-range temporal dependencies, which is pivotal for\n326\tdifferentiating between transient noise and sustained speech\n327\toverlaps. Through this process, SA-Encoder extracts the global\n328\tcontext representation Xglobal ∈ RT ×D . Subsequently, Xglobal\n329\tis transformed via the global router, which applies a linear\n330\tprojection and a softmax function to generate the global\n331\trouting probabilities Pglobal , which serve as a critical input\n332\tfor the holistic gating mechanism.\n333\tExplicit Supervision via Overlap-Aware Loss: Although\n334\tSA-Encoder extracts global context, without explicit guidance,\n335\tthe learned representations Xglobal remain semantically ungrounded. The model might rely on shortcut features, settling\n336\tinto suboptimal local minima. To enforce explicit acoustic\n337\tmodeling, we introduce the Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ).\n338\tAs illustrated in Fig. 1 (a), we utilize Xglobal to predict a frame-level overlap-aware sequence. As visualized in\n339\tFig. 2, we define the target sequence Yoverlap aware =\n340\t{y1 , y2 , . . . , yT }, where each token yt ∈ {0, 1, 2} represents\n341\tthe current speaker state:\n342\t• 0 (Padding): Represents padding frames during training.\n343\t• 1 (Single-Speaker): Represents frames where only one\n344\tspeaker is active.\n345\t• 2 (Overlap): Represents frames where speech from multiple speakers overlaps.\n346\tThe target sequence Yoverlap aware is automatically generated from the temporal boundaries determined by each source\n347\tutterance’s delay and duration. The delay is the offset time\n348\tat which the utterance is inserted into the mixture, while\n349\tthe duration reflects the length of the original clean segment;\n350\ttogether, they define the active time span of each speaker in\n351\tthe mixed signal.\n352\tCorrespondingly, the predicted overlap-aware sequence is\n353\tobtained by projecting the global context representation\n354\tXglobal through a classification head. The Overlap-Aware\n355\t\n356\tB. Holistic Gating Mechanism\n357\tEven with the robust acoustic states captured in Pglobal ,\n358\trelying solely on local features to determine the fusion ratio,\n359\tas done in previous works, creates an information asymmetry.\n360\tThis restricted perspective prevents the model from optimally\n361\tbalancing global context with local details. To address this,\n362\twe introduce the Holistic Gating Mechanism, which arbitrates\n363\texpert selection by jointly evaluating both information sources.\n364\tSpecifically, given the local features Xlocal ∈ RT ×D1 and\n365\tthe global context Xglobal ∈ RT ×D2 extracted from SAEncoder, we concatenate them to form a holistic representation. As illustrated in Fig. 1 (c), the fusion weights β ∈ RT ×2\n366\tare computed as:\n367\tXholistic = Concatenate(Xlocal , Xglobal ),\n368\tβ = sof tmax(Xholistic WHG + BHG ),\n369\t\n370\t(2)\n371\t\n372\twhere Xholistic ∈ RT ×(D1 +D2 ) represents the unified feature\n373\trepresentation. WHG ∈ R(D1 +D2 )×2 and BHG ∈ R2 denote\n374\tthe weight matrix and bias vector of the linear transformation,\n375\trespectively.\n376\tTo generate the final expert activation probabilities, we\n377\tutilize β to dynamically weight the local routing distribution Plocal ∈ RT ×N and the global routing distribution\n378\tPglobal ∈ RT ×N , where N is the number of experts. Let\n379\tβ0 , β1 ∈ RT ×1 denote the decomposed weights for the local\n380\tand global components derived from β, respectively. The final\n381\tprobability for the i-th expert, Pi ∈ RT ×1 , is obtained by:\n382\tPi = β0 ⊙ Plocal,i + β1 ⊙ Pglobal.i\n383\t\n384\t(3)\n385\t\n386\twhere ⊙ denotes element-wise multiplication.\n387\tOnce the final expert weights P are generated via this holistic view, the output of the MoLE layer is computed following\n388\tEq. 1. By adaptively integrating SA-Encoder-extracted speaker\n389\tcues with local phonetic details, the proposed mechanism\n390\tensures that expert usage is guided by a comprehensive perspective, thereby enhancing the model’s ability to disentangle\n391\tspeaker identity and transcribe spoken content.\n392\tC. Multi-Task Training Objective\n393\tTo jointly optimize the model for both accurate transcription and explicit acoustic cognition, we employ a multi-task\n394\tlearning strategy. The total objective function L is formulated\n395\tas a weighted sum of the primary recognition loss and the\n396\tauxiliary Overlap-Aware loss:\n397\tL = LASR + λLOA ,\n398\t\n399\t(4)\n400\t\n401\twhere LASR denotes the standard cross-entropy loss calculated on the serialized output targets for the MTASR task.\n402\tLOA is the auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss, which enforces the\n403\t\n404\t\fTABLE I: Training dataset composition\n405\tsingle-speaker\n406\tUtt.\n407\tDur.(hrs)\n408\t\n409\t202493\n410\t692.2\n411\t\n412\tLow\n413\t81808\n414\t491.8\n415\t\n416\t2-speaker\n417\tMid\n418\tHigh\n419\t75245\n420\t45423\n421\t383.0\n422\t203.2\n423\t\n424\tTotal\n425\t404985\n426\t1770.2\n427\t\n428\tlearning of discriminative acoustic states. The hyperparameter\n429\tλ controls the weight of the explicit acoustic supervision,\n430\tbalancing the trade-off between speaker disentanglement and\n431\ttranscription performance.\n432\tIV. E XPERIMENTAL S ETUP\n433\tA. Dataset\n434\tOur experiments are conducted on the LibriSpeechMix\n435\t(LSM) benchmark [6], which includes both 2-speaker (LSM2mix) and 3-speaker (LSM-3mix) scenarios derived from\n436\tLibriSpeech [14]. Given that the original LSM lacks a training\n437\tpartition, we construct a custom training set following the\n438\tprotocol in [7], [8], [11]. Specifically, we synthesize 2-speaker\n439\tmixtures by randomly pairing LibriSpeech utterances with\n440\tvarying temporal offsets. To construct the final training corpus,\n441\twe sample a subset of these simulated mixtures and combine\n442\tthem with a portion of the original single-speaker utterances.\n443\tTo facilitate a fine-grained evaluation across multi-talker\n444\tscenarios of varying complexity, we stratify the dataset based\n445\ton the overlap rate, defined as the duration of the overlapping segment divided by the total duration of the mixed\n446\tspeech. We categorize the data into three levels: Low (0, 0.2],\n447\tMedium (0.2, 0.5], and High (0.5, 1.0]. This division enables\n448\ta systematic analysis of model robustness under different\n449\tacoustic conditions. The detailed statistics and distribution of\n450\tthe resulting dataset are summarized in Table I.\n451\tB. Model Configuration and Training Setup\n452\tAll models are implemented using the ESPnet2 toolkit [15].\n453\tThe architecture follows an encoder-decoder framework, featuring a Conformer encoder [16] and a 6-block Transformer decoder. Regarding the internal structure, both encoder\n454\tand decoder blocks utilize 4-head self-attention with 256\n455\thidden units. In particular, the encoder employs macaronstyle blocks equipped with 1024-dimensional feed-forward\n456\tmodules, whereas the decoder blocks incorporate 2048dimensional feed-forward layers.\n457\tIn our experiments, SOT [6], SOT-SACTC [8], and GLADSOT [11] serve as the baseline systems. Additionally, to\n458\tevaluate the efficacy of MoE without global guidance, we implement an SOT + Local MoLE baseline, which incorporates\n459\tlocal Low-Rank experts but relies solely on local routing.\n460\tTo eliminate the influence of model size, we control the\n461\tnumber of encoder layers for each model to ensure parameter\n462\tparity. Accordingly, we assign 14 encoder layers to SOT, 13 to\n463\tSOT-SACTC, and 12 to SOT + Local MoLE, GLAD-SOT, and\n464\tour H-SAGE. As detailed in Table II, this setup guarantees that\n465\tall compared models possess a similar number of parameters.\n466\tFor baseline systems, we adopt the optimal hyperparameters\n467\treported in their respective papers. For H-SAGE, the MoLE\n468\t\n469\tmodule is configured with 3 experts, setting both the rank\n470\tr and scaling factor α in Eq. 1 to 8, while the OA-Loss\n471\tcoefficient λ in Eq. 4 is set to 3. All models are trained for\n472\t35 epochs. Training is performed on 8 NVIDIA GeForce RTX\n473\t3090 GPUs using the Adam optimizer with a peak learning\n474\trate of 5e−4 and 25,000 warm-up steps.\n475\tC. Evaluation Metrics\n476\tConsistent with prior studies [7], [8], [11], we evaluate\n477\tsingle-talker performance using Word Error Rate (WER).\n478\tFor multi-talker scenarios, we employ Permutation Invariant\n479\tWER (PI-WER) [6] to resolve speaker permutation ambiguity.\n480\tFurthermore, to provide a fine-grained assessment of robustness, we report Overlap-Aware WER (OA-WER), which is\n481\tcalculated by averaging the WERs across the stratified overlap\n482\tlevels defined previously.\n483\tIt is worth noting that while all models are trained exclusively on single-speaker and 2-speaker data, our evaluation\n484\textends to 3-speaker mixtures. Specifically, we use the singleand 2-speaker test sets to assess performance on in-domain\n485\tscenarios, whereas the 3-speaker test set is utilized to evaluate the model’s zero-shot generalization capability to unseen\n486\tspeaker numbers.\n487\tV. R ESULTS AND D ISCUSSION\n488\tIn this section, we validate H-SAGE, which demonstrates\n489\tsuperior performance over existing approaches (Tables II\n490\tand III). We provide a detailed analysis covering performance\n491\tcomparisons (Table II), followed by component-wise ablation\n492\tstudies (Table III) verifying the critical role of the proposed\n493\texplicit modeling and holistic routing mechanisms. Finally,\n494\twe examine the sensitivity of the auxiliary loss weight λ to\n495\tdetermine the optimal balance for explicit supervision.\n496\tA. Main Results\n497\tIn Table II, we benchmark the proposed H-SAGE (S5)\n498\tagainst representative baselines, analyzing the performance\n499\tevolution across different architectural paradigms.\n500\tPerformance Evolution of Baselines: First, comparing the\n501\tstandard SISO baseline SOT (S1) with SOT + Local MoLE\n502\t(S2), we observe that S2 achieves consistent improvements\n503\tdespite having fewer parameters. This confirms that the effectiveness of S2 stems from the efficient decomposition of diverse acoustic patterns via specialized local experts. Moreover,\n504\tSOT-SACTC [8] (S3) improves performance by introducing an\n505\texplicit separation constraint. By utilizing speaker-aware CTC,\n506\tS3 guides the encoder to learn disentangled speaker representations in the latent space, proving particularly effective in lowoverlap scenarios. Meanwhile, GLAD-SOT [11] (S4) advances\n507\tthe MoE paradigm of S2. Instead of relying on static local\n508\texperts, S4 employs a global-local routing mechanism. The\n509\tperformance of S4 demonstrates that for MoE architectures,\n510\tdynamic, context-aware expert selection is as critical as the\n511\texperts themselves.\n512\tSuperiority of H-SAGE: Building upon these advancements, H-SAGE (S5) addresses the structural limitations of\n513\t\n514\t\fTABLE II: Main performance comparison (WER %) against state-of-the-art baselines on LibriSpeech and LibriSpeechMix\n515\tbenchmarks. Consistent with standard protocols, all models are trained on a unified dataset comprising single-talker and twotalker utterances. The best and second-best results are highlighted in bold underline and underline, respectively.\n516\tLibrispeech\n517\tSystem\n518\t\n519\tMethod\n520\t\n521\tParm.(M)\n522\t\n523\tS1\n524\tS2\n525\tS3\n526\tS4\n527\tS5\n528\t\n529\tSOT [6]\n530\tSOT + Local MoLE\n531\tSOT-SACTC [8]\n532\tGLAD-SOT [11]\n533\tH-SAGE\n534\t\n535\t36.07\n536\t35.09\n537\t35.77\n538\t35.18\n539\t35.75\n540\t\n541\tDev\n542\t\n543\tTest\n544\t\n545\t4.1\n546\t3.7\n547\t3.6\n548\t3.5\n549\t3.6\n550\t\n551\t4.5\n552\t3.8\n553\t3.8\n554\t3.9\n555\t3.8\n556\t\n557\tOverall\n558\tDev\n559\tTest\n560\t8.5\n561\t8.3\n562\t6.4\n563\t6.5\n564\t6.9\n565\t6.7\n566\t6.0\n567\t6.2\n568\t6.0\n569\t5.7\n570\t\n571\tLSM-2mix\n572\tTest(Conditional)\n573\tlow mid high\n574\tOA-WER\n575\t6.2\n576\t8.9\n577\t12.8\n578\t9.3\n579\t5.3\n580\t6.3\n581\t10.3\n582\t7.3\n583\t4.8\n584\t7.2\n585\t10.8\n586\t7.6\n587\t5.1\n588\t6.4\n589\t8.9\n590\t6.8\n591\t4.7\n592\t5.7\n593\t8.2\n594\t6.2\n595\t\n596\tGLAD and achieves the best overall performance. On the\n597\tsingle-speaker LibriSpeech benchmark, H-SAGE maintains\n598\tparity with strong baselines, confirming that the model incurs\n599\tno degradation in clean scenarios. In the two-speaker mixtures\n600\t(LSM-2mix), S5 consistently surpasses all baselines, achieving\n601\tnotable improvements in the challenging mid and high overlap\n602\tconditions. These results suggest that by explicitly modeling\n603\toverlap states, H-SAGE effectively resolves complex feature\n604\tentanglement that hinders previous methods.\n605\tZero-Shot Generalization (LSM-3mix): The advantages\n606\tof H-SAGE are most pronounced in the zero-shot LSM-3mix\n607\tscenario, which evaluates generalization to unseen speaker\n608\tcounts. While baselines struggle to maintain performance,\n609\tH-SAGE maintains a significant lead overall, particularly in\n610\tcomplex high-overlap scenarios. We note a performance gap\n611\tin the LSM-3mix-Low compared to SACTC. This is intuitive:\n612\tSACTC’s explicit separation constraints are highly efficient\n613\tfor sparse, easy-to-separate segments. In contrast, H-SAGE is\n614\toptimized for complex entanglement. Nevertheless, H-SAGE’s\n615\tdominance in the more realistic mid and high overlap scenarios\n616\tvalidates its superior robustness and generalization capability\n617\twhere it matters most.\n618\tB. Ablation Study\n619\tAs summarized in Tables III, we conduct an ablation study\n620\t(S5–S8) to validate the contributions of core components.\n621\tEffectiveness of Explicit Acoustic Supervision: We compare the full model (S5) against the variant without explicit\n622\tsupervision (S6) to validate the role of LOA . On the clean\n623\tLibrispeech dataset, S5 exhibits a marginal performance drop\n624\tcompared to S6. This can be attributed to the interference\n625\tfrom the auxiliary objective. For clean speech, explicit overlap detection is redundant. Consequently, the auxiliary task\n626\tintroduces optimization noise that marginally degrades S5\n627\tcompared to S6 in the single-speaker scenario.\n628\tHowever, in the in-domain LSM-2mix scenario, S5 surpasses S6. This indicates that explicit supervision effectively\n629\tsharpens the router’s decision boundaries, enabling more precise expert specialization than implicit learning alone. Most\n630\tnotably, S5 achieves substantial gains over S6 in the zeroshot LSM-3mix scenario. This result highlights the critical\n631\tvalue of LOA for generalization. In contrast to S6, which\n632\ttends to overfit to two-speaker patterns, S5 leverages explicit\n633\tsupervision to capture a generic overlap state. This enables\n634\t\n635\tLSM-3mix (zero-shot generalization)\n636\tOverall\n637\tTest(Conditional)\n638\tDev\n639\tTest\n640\tlow\n641\tmid\n642\thigh OA-WER\n643\t23.8\n644\t24.2\n645\t17.1\n646\t23.8\n647\t32.3\n648\t24.4\n649\t21.1\n650\t21.7\n651\t15.3\n652\t21.6\n653\t28.5\n654\t21.8\n655\t20.6\n656\t20.0\n657\t12.8\n658\t20.0\n659\t27.2\n660\t20.0\n661\t19.9\n662\t19.8\n663\t15.0\n664\t19.5\n665\t25.5\n666\t20.0\n667\t19.7\n668\t19.5\n669\t15.5\n670\t18.9\n671\t24.9\n672\t19.8\n673\t\n674\tTABLE III: Ablation study and architectural analysis on the\n675\tLibriSpeechMix benchmark.\n676\tSystem\n677\t\n678\tMethod\n679\t\n680\tLibrispeech\n681\t\n682\tLSM-2mix\n683\t\n684\tDev\n685\t\n686\tTest\n687\t\n688\tDev\n689\t\n690\tTest\n691\t\n692\tLSM-3mix\n693\t(zero-shot)\n694\tDev\n695\tTest\n696\t\n697\t3.6\n698\t\n699\t3.8\n700\t\n701\t6.0\n702\t\n703\t5.7\n704\t\n705\t19.7\n706\t\n707\t19.5\n708\t\n709\tS6\n710\tS7\n711\tS8\n712\t\n713\tw/o OA-Loss\n714\tw/o SA-Encoder + OA-Loss\n715\tw/o holistic gating\n716\t\n717\t3.5\n718\t3.6\n719\t3.4\n720\t\n721\t3.7\n722\t4.0\n723\t3.9\n724\t\n725\t6.1\n726\t6.2\n727\t6.0\n728\t\n729\t5.8\n730\t6.4\n731\t6.2\n732\t\n733\t20.2\n734\t20.8\n735\t20.4\n736\t\n737\t20.1\n738\t21.5\n739\t20.9\n740\t\n741\tS9\n742\tS10\n743\t\n744\tw MoLE only in FFN\n745\tw MoLE only in Att.\n746\t\n747\t3.9\n748\t3.3\n749\t\n750\t4.2\n751\t3.7\n752\t\n753\t6.8\n754\t6.3\n755\t\n756\t6.4\n757\t6.0\n758\t\n759\t21.2\n760\t20.2\n761\t\n762\t21.3\n763\t20.3\n764\t\n765\tS5\n766\t\n767\tH-SAGE\n768\t\n769\trobust generalization to unseen scenarios with more speakers,\n770\tdemonstrating the vital role of explicit supervision.\n771\tNecessity of Long-Range Temporal Modeling: To isolate\n772\tthe structural contribution of the global encoder, we compare\n773\tS6 (H-SAGE w/o OA-Loss LOA ) against S7 (H-SAGE w/o\n774\tSA-Encoder). It is important to note that in S7, the absence of\n775\tthe SA-Encoder implies that the global encoder degenerates to\n776\tthe simple frame-independent linear projection used in GLAD.\n777\tThe results show that S6 yields consistent improvements\n778\tover S7 across the majority of metrics. This indicates that even\n779\twithout explicit supervision, the self-attention structure of SAEncoder inherently captures long-range temporal dependencies\n780\tinaccessible to the linear projection in S7. Unlike the instantaneous mapping in S7, SA-Encoder aggregates information\n781\tacross the sequence, proving that modeling temporal evolution\n782\tof speech is a prerequisite for robust expert assignment.\n783\tNecessity of Holistic Gating Mechanism: We compare HSAGE (S5) with the variant excluding holistic gating (S8).\n784\tNote that in S8, the router degenerates to the GLAD fusion\n785\tmechanism, relying solely on the current layer’s features.\n786\tWe observe comparable performance in the single-speaker\n787\tscenario. This suggests that in clean acoustic environments,\n788\tlocal features provide sufficient guidance. However, H-SAGE\n789\tconsistently outperforms S8 across all other benchmarks,\n790\tincluding in-domain LSM-2mix and zero-shot LSM-3mix scenarios. This confirms that while local cues suffice for simple\n791\ttasks, the holistic view is indispensable for resolving complex\n792\tfeature entanglement in challenging multi-talker environments.\n793\tC. Architectural Analysis\n794\tAs summarized in Table III, we analyze expert placement\n795\tacross the full H-SAGE (S5), the variant with experts applied\n796\tonly to Feed-Forward Networks (FFN) (S9), and the Attentiononly variant (S10). In terms of performance, S5 achieves the\n797\t\n798\t\f6.61\n799\t6.51\n800\t\n801\t6.45\n802\t\n803\tOA-WER\n804\t\n805\tOA-WER\n806\t\n807\t6.7\n808\t6.6\n809\t6.5 6.45\n810\t6.38\n811\t6.4\n812\t6.3\n813\t6.2\n814\t6.1\n815\t0 1\n816\t\n817\t6.2\n818\t\n819\t3\n820\t5\n821\t7\n822\tLambda Value\n823\t\n824\t10\n825\t\n826\t(a) Performance on LSM-2mix\n827\t\n828\t21.0\n829\t20.8\n830\t20.6\n831\t20.4 20.24\n832\t20.2 20.02\n833\t20.0\n834\t19.8\n835\t19.6\n836\t19.4\n837\t0 1\n838\t\n839\t20.78\n840\t20.56\n841\t\n842\t20.02\n843\t19.78\n844\t\n845\t3\n846\t5\n847\t7\n848\tLambda Value\n849\t\n850\t10\n851\t\n852\t(b) Performance on LSM-3mix\n853\t\n854\tFig. 3: Impact of the auxiliary loss weight λ on OA-WER\n855\tperformance.\n856\tbest results, followed by S10, with S9 trailing. This ranking\n857\tconfirms that deploying experts in both modules yields a\n858\tsynergistic effect, maximizing the capacity to handle complex\n859\tacoustic variations.\n860\tNotably, our analysis reveals a correlation between global\n861\tmodeling strength and optimal expert placement. In prior\n862\tMoE-based MTASR studies, although attention experts are\n863\toften regarded as crucial, FFN experts can outperform them in\n864\tcertain scenarios due to stronger feature transformation capabilities. However, the introduction of the SA-Encoder enhances\n865\tthe effectiveness of attention experts. Our experiments show\n866\tS10 consistently outperforms S9, indicating that when global\n867\tfeatures are robustly captured, expert specialization within the\n868\tattention mechanism becomes pivotal. Inherently designed for\n869\tsequence modeling, the attention mechanism is structurally\n870\tcompatible with global cues from the SA-Encoder. This allows\n871\tit to effectively utilize these cues for speaker disentanglement.\n872\tThus, while FFN experts provide limited support in certain\n873\tscenarios, attention-based experts become more critical once\n874\tthe acoustic state is effectively modeled.\n875\tD. Impact of Auxiliary Loss Weight λ\n876\tWe evaluate the auxiliary weight λ in Eq. 4 across the set\n877\t{0, 1, 3, 5, 7, 10}. As illustrated in Fig. 3, we observe that λ =\n878\t3 consistently yields optimal performance for both in-domain\n879\t(LSM-2mix) and zero-shot (LSM-3mix) scenarios. Notably,\n880\twhile the trend in the simpler 2-mix scenario shows slight\n881\tfluctuations, the more challenging 3-mix scenario exhibits a\n882\tdistinct U-shaped pattern. This indicates that while the model\n883\thandles in-domain data relatively easily, explicit supervision\n884\tof speaker activity states becomes critical for generalizing\n885\tto complex, unseen acoustic environments. However, further\n886\tincreasing λ beyond 3 leads to degradation in both cases, as an\n887\toverly dominant auxiliary objective overshadows the primary\n888\ttranscription task. Consequently, we set λ = 3 to balance\n889\toverlap awareness and ASR accuracy.\n890\tVI. C ONCLUSION\n891\tIn this paper, we propose Holistic Speaker-Aware Guided\n892\tExperts (H-SAGE), a framework that shifts MoE-based\n893\tMTASR from implicit adaptation to explicit acoustic modeling. By integrating a Speaker-Aware Global Encoder with\n894\ta Holistic Gating Mechanism, H-SAGE captures dynamic\n895\tspeaker states and improves expert selection. Experiments\n896\t\n897\ton LibriSpeechMix show that H-SAGE outperforms stateof-the-art methods, especially under high-overlap conditions.\n898\tFurthermore, ablation analyses confirm that explicit acoustic\n899\tsupervision and a holistic view are indispensable for disentangling speakers in complex environments.\n900\tR EFERENCES\n901\t[1] Xinlu He and Jacob Whitehill, “Survey of end-to-end multi-speaker\n902\tautomatic speech recognition for monaural audio,” arXiv preprint\n903\tarXiv:2505.10975, 2025.\n904\t[2] Dong Yu, Xuankai Chang, and Yanmin Qian, “Recognizing multitalker speech with permutation invariant training,” arXiv preprint\n905\tarXiv:1704.01985, 2017.\n906\t[3] Shane Settle, Jonathan Le Roux, Takaaki Hori, Shinji Watanabe, and\n907\tJohn R Hershey, “End-to-end multi-speaker speech recognition,” in\n908\t2018 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal\n909\tprocessing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2018, pp. 4819–4823.\n910\t[4] Xuankai Chang, Wangyou Zhang, Yanmin Qian, Jonathan Le Roux, and\n911\tShinji Watanabe, “End-to-end multi-speaker speech recognition with\n912\ttransformer,” in ICASSP 2020-2020 IEEE International Conference on\n913\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2020, pp.\n914\t6134–6138.\n915\t[5] Dong Yu, Morten Kolbæk, Zheng-Hua Tan, and Jesper Jensen, “Permutation invariant training of deep models for speaker-independent multitalker speech separation,” in 2017 IEEE International Conference on\n916\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2017, pp.\n917\t241–245.\n918\t[6] Naoyuki Kanda, Yashesh Gaur, Xiaofei Wang, Zhong Meng, and Takuya\n919\tYoshioka, “Serialized output training for end-to-end overlapped speech\n920\trecognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2003.12687, 2020.\n921\t[7] Jiawen Kang, Lingwei Meng, Mingyu Cui, Haohan Guo, Xixin Wu,\n922\tXunying Liu, and Helen Meng, “Cross-speaker encoding network\n923\tfor multi-talker speech recognition,” in ICASSP 2024-2024 IEEE\n924\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n925\t(ICASSP). IEEE, 2024, pp. 11986–11990.\n926\t[8] Jiawen Kang, Lingwei Meng, Mingyu Cui, Yuejiao Wang, Xixin Wu,\n927\tXunying Liu, and Helen Meng, “Disentangling speakers in multi-talker\n928\tspeech recognition with speaker-aware ctc,” in ICASSP 2025-2025 IEEE\n929\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n930\t(ICASSP). IEEE, 2025, pp. 1–5.\n931\t[9] Asahi Sakuma, Hiroaki Sato, Ryuga Sugano, Tadashi Kumano, Yoshihiko Kawai, and Tetsuji Ogawa, “Speaker-distinguishable ctc: Learning\n932\tspeaker distinction using ctc for multi-talker speech recognition,” arXiv\n933\tpreprint arXiv:2506.07515, 2025.\n934\t[10] Weiqing Wang, Taejin Park, Ivan Medennikov, Jinhan Wang, Kunal\n935\tDhawan, He Huang, Nithin Rao Koluguri, Jagadeesh Balam, and Boris\n936\tGinsburg, “Speaker targeting via self-speaker adaptation for multi-talker\n937\tasr,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2506.22646, 2025.\n938\t[11] Yujie Guo, Jiaming Zhou, Yuhang Jia, Shiwan Zhao, and Yong Qin,\n939\t“Glad: Global-local aware dynamic mixture-of-experts for multi-talker\n940\tasr,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2509.13093, 2025.\n941\t[12] Chongyang Gao, Kezhen Chen, Jinmeng Rao, Ruibo Liu, Baochen\n942\tSun, Yawen Zhang, Daiyi Peng, Xiaoyuan Guo, and VS Subrahmanian,\n943\t“Mola: Moe lora with layer-wise expert allocation,” in Findings of\n944\tthe Association for Computational Linguistics: NAACL 2025, 2025, pp.\n945\t5097–5112.\n946\t[13] Edward J Hu, Yelong Shen, Phillip Wallis, Zeyuan Allen-Zhu, Yuanzhi\n947\tLi, Shean Wang, Lu Wang, Weizhu Chen, et al., “Lora: Low-rank\n948\tadaptation of large language models.,” ICLR, vol. 1, no. 2, pp. 3, 2022.\n949\t[14] Vassil Panayotov, Guoguo Chen, Daniel Povey, and Sanjeev Khudanpur,\n950\t“Librispeech: an asr corpus based on public domain audio books,” in\n951\t2015 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal\n952\tprocessing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n953\t[15] Shinji Watanabe, Takaaki Hori, Shigeki Karita, Tomoki Hayashi, Jiro\n954\tNishitoba, Yuya Unno, Nelson Enrique Yalta Soplin, Jahn Heymann,\n955\tMatthew Wiesner, Nanxin Chen, Adithya Renduchintala, and Tsubasa\n956\tOchiai, “ESPnet: End-to-end speech processing toolkit,” in Proceedings\n957\tof Interspeech, 2018, pp. 2207–2211.\n958\t[16] Anmol Gulati, James Qin, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Niki Parmar, Yu Zhang,\n959\tJiahui Yu, Wei Han, Shibo Wang, Zhengdong Zhang, Yonghui Wu,\n960\tet al., “Conformer: Convolution-augmented transformer for speech\n961\trecognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2005.08100, 2020.\n962\t\n963\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fdf55927-452e-43d8-b855-4fbaaac4fe27", "uuid": "e15ff31c-5b9e-4c2a-83b2-318084157cac", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T07:56:34.216Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/hsage_paper.txt", "content": "H-SAGE: Holistic Speaker-Aware Guided Experts\nfor MoE-based Multi-Talker ASR\nYujie Guo1 , Jiaming Zhou1 , Yuhang Jia1 , Yang Chen1 , and Yong Qin1,∗\n1\n\narXiv:2607.01566v1 [cs.SD] 2 Jul 2026\n\nTMCC, College of Computer Science, Nankai University, Tianjin, China\n{guoyujie02,zhoujiaming,2120240729,2120230617}@mail.nankai.edu.cn, qinyong@nankai.edu.cn\n\nAbstract—Multi-talker\nAutomatic\nSpeech\nRecognition\n(MTASR) faces significant challenges in accurately transcribing\noverlapping speech, particularly under complex high-overlap\nconditions. While recent Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) approaches\nhave shown promise, they typically rely on frame-independent\nrouting that leads to temporal myopia, and depend solely on\nthe downstream ASR objective, which results in implicit and\nungrounded representation learning. To address these limitations,\nwe propose Holistic Speaker-Aware Guided Experts (H-SAGE)\nfor MoE-based MTASR. Specifically, we introduce a SpeakerAware Global Encoder to capture long-term dependencies,\nsupervised by an auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss that explicitly\nguides the model to discern acoustic states. Furthermore,\nwe design a Holistic Gating Mechanism to arbitrate expert\nselection by jointly evaluating global context and local details.\nExperiments on LibriSpeechMix demonstrate that H-SAGE\nachieves consistent improvements over strong baselines,\nparticularly in complex scenarios, validating that explicit\nacoustic guidance effectively enhances expert collaboration. Our\ncode can be found at https://github.com/NKU-HLT/H-SAGE.\nIndex Terms—multi-talker automatic speech recognition, cocktail party problem, Mixture-of-Experts, speaker-aware\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nIn recent years, Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) has\nwitnessed remarkable progress due to the advent of deep\nlearning. State-of-the-art architectures have achieved humanlevel performance in clean, single-speaker scenarios. However,\nthese systems often degrade significantly in realistic conversational environments, which are characterized by spontaneous\nturn-taking and frequent speech overlaps. This limitation has\ncatalyzed the emergence of Multi-Talker ASR (MTASR) as\na critical research frontier. Unlike traditional ASR, which\nassumes a monotonic mapping between a single acoustic\nstream and text, MTASR aims to simultaneously disentangle\nand transcribe overlapping utterances from multiple speakers,\naddressing the classic “Cocktail Party Problem”.\nCurrent end-to-end MTASR approaches fall into two\nparadigms: Single-Input Multiple-Output (SIMO) and SingleInput Single-Output (SISO) [1]. SIMO-based methods [2]–\n[4] utilize Permutation Invariant Training (PIT) [5] to assign\nspeech to specific branches. While effective, they are constrained by a fixed number of output branches, limiting their\nflexibility when the speaker count is unknown or variable.\nIn contrast, SISO approaches employ Serialized Output\nTraining (SOT) [6] to generate a serialized transcription con∗ Corresponding author. This work was supported by the National Natural\nScience Foundation of China (62271270).\n\ntaining all speakers. This paradigm inherently handles variable\nspeaker counts, offering superior flexibility. However, it relies\nheavily on the attention mechanism to implicitly disentangle\noverlapping speech. Without explicit guidance, the model often\nstruggles to distinguish speakers in high-overlap segments,\nresulting in performance degradation.\nTo mitigate this issue, recent research has pivoted towards\naugmenting SISO frameworks with explicit speaker modeling,\nutilizing auxiliary modules or objectives to capture discriminative speaker characteristics. For instance, CSE-SOT [7]\nemploys multi-branch structures to capture distinct speaker\nrepresentation. Similarly, SACTC [8] and SD-CTC [9] leverage improved connectionist temporal classification to explicitly guide the encoders in separating speaker information.\nFurthermore, SSA [10] utilizes an external diarization system\nto explicitly provide speaker activity cues, guiding the ASR\nmodel to generate speaker-specific transcriptions.\nParallel to these advancements, the Mixture-of-Experts\n(MoE) paradigm has recently been explored in MTASR, with\nGLAD [11] representing an early attempt. Despite integrating\nglobal and local routers, GLAD suffers from key structural\nlimitations. Its global information relies on frame-independent\nprojections, preventing effective modeling of speaker-level\ntemporal dynamics. Moreover, its speaker-aware behavior is\nlearned only implicitly through the standard ASR training\nobjective, making the router prone to shortcut learning rather\nthan acquiring robust discriminative cues. Finally, its expert\nselection strategy is derived solely from local representations,\ngiving the router a narrow, non-holistic perspective that limits\nits adaptability to complex acoustic conditions.\nTo address these issues, we propose Holistic SpeakerAware Guided Experts (H-SAGE), a framework that rethinks\nexpert routing for MoE-based MTASR. H-SAGE comprises\ntwo complementary components: a Speaker-Aware Global\nEncoder (SA-Encoder) that explicitly models speaker activity\nstates—such as silence, single-speaker, and overlap—guided\nby an auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ), and a Holistic\nGating Mechanism that assigns experts by jointly leveraging\nglobal acoustic context and local frame-level cues. Together,\nthese components deliver more reliable and context-informed\nrouting decisions, addressing the core limitations of prior\nMoE-based approaches. Our contributions are as follows:\n• We propose H-SAGE, a novel framework anchored by a\nSA-Encoder. Supervised by an auxiliary Overlap-Aware\nLoss, this design captures evolving acoustic states and\n\n\f𝓛ASR\n\n𝓛OA\nTarget\nOA-Sequence\n\nCompute\nLoss\n\nCompute\nLoss\n\nGround\nTruth\n\nPredict Transcription\nOA-Sequence\n\n𝑷𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n\n𝑶𝒖𝒕\n\n𝑿𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n\n+\nGlobal\nRouter\n\nWeighted\nSum\n\n𝑷\n\nTransformer\nDecoder\n\n+\n\n𝑷𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n\n\n\n+\n\n\n\nLinear\n\n𝑷𝒍𝒐𝒄𝒂𝒍\n\nFeed Forward\n\n𝑿𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n\nConformer\nEncoder\n\nSA-Encoder\n\nLinear\n\n+\n\n𝑷𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n\nMulti-Head\nSelf Attention\n\nSA-Encoder\n\nSA-Encoder\n\n𝑿𝒈𝒍𝒐𝒃𝒂𝒍\n\nLocal\nRouter\n\n𝑩𝟏\n\n𝑩𝟐\n\n𝑨𝟏\n\n𝑨𝟐\n\n𝑩𝑵\n\n…\n𝑨𝑵\n\nShared\nLinear\n\nc\n\nHolistic Gating\nA MoLE Layer in Conformer\n\n𝑿𝒔𝒑𝒆𝒆𝒄𝒉\n\n𝑿𝒔𝒑𝒆𝒆𝒄𝒉\n(a) Training of H-SAGE\n\n(b) Structure of SA-Encoder\n\n𝑿𝒔𝒑𝒆𝒆𝒄𝒉\n\n𝑿𝒍𝒐𝒄𝒂𝒍\n(c) MoLE with Holistic Gating used in H-SAGE\n\nFig. 1: Overview of the H-SAGE architecture. (a) Training Pipeline: The Conformer Encoder integrates the MoLE blocks shown\nin (c). The model is jointly optimized by LASR and the explicit Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ). (b) Structure of SA-Encoder:\nSA-Encoder extracts global context from the convolutional frontend output Xspeech , producing global routing probabilities\nPglobal and context features Xglobal . (c) MoLE used in H-SAGE: Detailed structure of the MoLE block. These blocks replace\nall the linear transformations in the Conformer Encoder. The Holistic Gating mechanism fuses global context (Xglobal ) and\nlocal input (Xlocal ) to adaptively balance routing probabilities for precise expert selection.\nshifts the routing paradigm from implicit representation\nlearning to explicit acoustic modeling.\n• We introduce a Holistic Gating Mechanism to optimize\nexpert assignment. By synthesizing global acoustic contexts with local representations, it ensures a comprehensive perspective for robust expert selection.\n• Experiments on LibriSpeechMix demonstrate consistent\nimprovements over strong baselines in multi-talker scenarios. Crucially, further analysis validates the effectiveness of the proposed mechanisms, confirming their role in\nexpert collaboration and robust speaker disentanglement.\nII. P RELIMINARY K NOWLEDGE\nA. Serialized Output Training\nSerialized Output Training (SOT) [6] serves as a prominent\nSingle-Input Single-Output (SISO) paradigm in MTASR. In\ncontrast to architectures relying on multiple output branches,\nSOT leverages a single decoder to transcribe overlapping\nspeech from a variable number of speakers into a unified\nsequence. Given an utterance with N speakers, the model\nis trained to generate a concatenated sequence formatted as\nY = {text1 , ⟨sc⟩, text2 , . . . , ⟨sc⟩, textN }, where texti represents the transcription sequence of the i-th speaker, and ⟨sc⟩\ndenotes a special speaker-change token. We adopt the FirstIn, First-Out (FIFO) strategy, organizing transcripts chronologically based on speaker onset. This serialization strategy\nallows the model to implicitly disentangle overlapping speech,\neffectively bypassing the combinatorial complexity associated\nwith permutation-based methods.\nB. MoE-based MTASR\nGLAD [11] represents a pioneering effort in applying the\nMixture-of-Low-Rank-Experts (MoLE) paradigm to MTASR.\nIt replaces all linear layers within the encoder with MoLE\n\nblocks, whose structure resembles MoE-LoRA [12]. Given an\ninput feature X ∈ Rdin , the output is formulated as:\nα PN\nY = WX +\nPi Bi Ai X + b,\n(1)\nr i=1\nwhere W and b denote the weights and bias of the shared\nlinear layer, respectively. Adopting the structural design of\nLoRA [13], each Low-Rank expert is parameterized by lowrank matrices Ai ∈ Rr×din and Bi ∈ Rdout ×r with rank\nr ≪ min(din , dout ), scaled by a factor α. The expert weight\nPi is computed via a gating mechanism that combines global\nand local routing signals.\nThe expert activation weight Pi is computed via a gating\nmechanism that combines global and local routing signals.\nSpecifically, GLAD employs a linear projection on the convolutional frontend output to derive a frame-independent global\nrouter, while the local router is derived from the current\nlayer’s hidden states. The fusion coefficient is derived from the\ncurrent layer’s features to balance these signals. Consequently,\nthe final routing weight fuses the frame-independent global\nprojection with instantaneous local representations.\nIII. O UR M ETHODS\nAs illustrated in Fig. 1 (a), H-SAGE is built upon an MoEbased encoder-decoder architecture. Consistent with prior\nwork [11], we replace standard linear layers in the encoder\nwith MoLE blocks. Uniquely, our architecture integrates two\nkey modules: the SA-Encoder module (Fig. 1 (b)), which\ncaptures global acoustic context supervised by the OverlapAware Loss, and the Holistic Gating Mechanism (Fig. 1\n(c)), which synthesizes global acoustic contexts with local\nrepresentations for expert routing.\nA. Speaker-Aware Global Encoder with Explicit Supervision\nTo transition from implicit adaptation to explicit acoustic modeling, we introduce SA-Encoder. Unlike frame-\n\n\fSpeaker2\n\nSpeaker1\n\nMixed wave\n\nTarget overlap-aware\nsequence\n\n𝐓3\n\n𝐓2\n\n𝐓𝟏\n\n𝐓4\n\nT : number of frames\n0 : padding frames\n1 : frames where only one speaker is\nactive\n2 : frames containing overlapping\nspeech from multiple speakers\n\nLoss LOA is then computed as the Cross-Entropy between\nthe predictions and the targets Yoverlap aware . Minimizing\nthis objective explicitly supervises the model to distinguish\nbetween single-talker and multi-talker segments, providing\nrobust guidance for expert selection.\n\n[𝟏. . . 𝟏, 2. . . 2, 𝟏. . . 𝟏, 𝟎. . . 𝟎]\n𝐓𝟏\n\n𝐓2\n\n𝐓3\n\n𝐓4\n\n𝓛 OA (Compute loss using Cross-entropy loss)\n\nPredicted overlap-aware sequence\n\nFig. 2: The detail of Overlap-Aware Loss\nindependent projections that suffer from temporal myopia, SAEncoder is designed to capture dynamic speaker activity states\nvia long-term dependency modeling, explicitly supervised by\nan auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ).\nSA-Encoder: As illustrated in Fig. 1 (b), SA-Encoder operates directly on the signals Xspeech ∈ RT ×D extracted by the\nconvolutional frontend. This design effectively preserves rich\nacoustic characteristics that are often diluted in deeper network\nlayers. Deviating from simple linear projection, SA-Encoder\nincorporates a Multi-Head Self-Attention block followed by a\nFeed-Forward Network. This architecture enables the model to\ncapture long-range temporal dependencies, which is pivotal for\ndifferentiating between transient noise and sustained speech\noverlaps. Through this process, SA-Encoder extracts the global\ncontext representation Xglobal ∈ RT ×D . Subsequently, Xglobal\nis transformed via the global router, which applies a linear\nprojection and a softmax function to generate the global\nrouting probabilities Pglobal , which serve as a critical input\nfor the holistic gating mechanism.\nExplicit Supervision via Overlap-Aware Loss: Although\nSA-Encoder extracts global context, without explicit guidance,\nthe learned representations Xglobal remain semantically ungrounded. The model might rely on shortcut features, settling\ninto suboptimal local minima. To enforce explicit acoustic\nmodeling, we introduce the Overlap-Aware Loss (LOA ).\nAs illustrated in Fig. 1 (a), we utilize Xglobal to predict a frame-level overlap-aware sequence. As visualized in\nFig. 2, we define the target sequence Yoverlap aware =\n{y1 , y2 , . . . , yT }, where each token yt ∈ {0, 1, 2} represents\nthe current speaker state:\n• 0 (Padding): Represents padding frames during training.\n• 1 (Single-Speaker): Represents frames where only one\nspeaker is active.\n• 2 (Overlap): Represents frames where speech from multiple speakers overlaps.\nThe target sequence Yoverlap aware is automatically generated from the temporal boundaries determined by each source\nutterance’s delay and duration. The delay is the offset time\nat which the utterance is inserted into the mixture, while\nthe duration reflects the length of the original clean segment;\ntogether, they define the active time span of each speaker in\nthe mixed signal.\nCorrespondingly, the predicted overlap-aware sequence is\nobtained by projecting the global context representation\nXglobal through a classification head. The Overlap-Aware\n\nB. Holistic Gating Mechanism\nEven with the robust acoustic states captured in Pglobal ,\nrelying solely on local features to determine the fusion ratio,\nas done in previous works, creates an information asymmetry.\nThis restricted perspective prevents the model from optimally\nbalancing global context with local details. To address this,\nwe introduce the Holistic Gating Mechanism, which arbitrates\nexpert selection by jointly evaluating both information sources.\nSpecifically, given the local features Xlocal ∈ RT ×D1 and\nthe global context Xglobal ∈ RT ×D2 extracted from SAEncoder, we concatenate them to form a holistic representation. As illustrated in Fig. 1 (c), the fusion weights β ∈ RT ×2\nare computed as:\nXholistic = Concatenate(Xlocal , Xglobal ),\nβ = sof tmax(Xholistic WHG + BHG ),\n\n(2)\n\nwhere Xholistic ∈ RT ×(D1 +D2 ) represents the unified feature\nrepresentation. WHG ∈ R(D1 +D2 )×2 and BHG ∈ R2 denote\nthe weight matrix and bias vector of the linear transformation,\nrespectively.\nTo generate the final expert activation probabilities, we\nutilize β to dynamically weight the local routing distribution Plocal ∈ RT ×N and the global routing distribution\nPglobal ∈ RT ×N , where N is the number of experts. Let\nβ0 , β1 ∈ RT ×1 denote the decomposed weights for the local\nand global components derived from β, respectively. The final\nprobability for the i-th expert, Pi ∈ RT ×1 , is obtained by:\nPi = β0 ⊙ Plocal,i + β1 ⊙ Pglobal.i\n\n(3)\n\nwhere ⊙ denotes element-wise multiplication.\nOnce the final expert weights P are generated via this holistic view, the output of the MoLE layer is computed following\nEq. 1. By adaptively integrating SA-Encoder-extracted speaker\ncues with local phonetic details, the proposed mechanism\nensures that expert usage is guided by a comprehensive perspective, thereby enhancing the model’s ability to disentangle\nspeaker identity and transcribe spoken content.\nC. Multi-Task Training Objective\nTo jointly optimize the model for both accurate transcription and explicit acoustic cognition, we employ a multi-task\nlearning strategy. The total objective function L is formulated\nas a weighted sum of the primary recognition loss and the\nauxiliary Overlap-Aware loss:\nL = LASR + λLOA ,\n\n(4)\n\nwhere LASR denotes the standard cross-entropy loss calculated on the serialized output targets for the MTASR task.\nLOA is the auxiliary Overlap-Aware Loss, which enforces the\n\n\fTABLE I: Training dataset composition\nsingle-speaker\nUtt.\nDur.(hrs)\n\n202493\n692.2\n\nLow\n81808\n491.8\n\n2-speaker\nMid\nHigh\n75245\n45423\n383.0\n203.2\n\nTotal\n404985\n1770.2\n\nlearning of discriminative acoustic states. The hyperparameter\nλ controls the weight of the explicit acoustic supervision,\nbalancing the trade-off between speaker disentanglement and\ntranscription performance.\nIV. E XPERIMENTAL S ETUP\nA. Dataset\nOur experiments are conducted on the LibriSpeechMix\n(LSM) benchmark [6], which includes both 2-speaker (LSM2mix) and 3-speaker (LSM-3mix) scenarios derived from\nLibriSpeech [14]. Given that the original LSM lacks a training\npartition, we construct a custom training set following the\nprotocol in [7], [8], [11]. Specifically, we synthesize 2-speaker\nmixtures by randomly pairing LibriSpeech utterances with\nvarying temporal offsets. To construct the final training corpus,\nwe sample a subset of these simulated mixtures and combine\nthem with a portion of the original single-speaker utterances.\nTo facilitate a fine-grained evaluation across multi-talker\nscenarios of varying complexity, we stratify the dataset based\non the overlap rate, defined as the duration of the overlapping segment divided by the total duration of the mixed\nspeech. We categorize the data into three levels: Low (0, 0.2],\nMedium (0.2, 0.5], and High (0.5, 1.0]. This division enables\na systematic analysis of model robustness under different\nacoustic conditions. The detailed statistics and distribution of\nthe resulting dataset are summarized in Table I.\nB. Model Configuration and Training Setup\nAll models are implemented using the ESPnet2 toolkit [15].\nThe architecture follows an encoder-decoder framework, featuring a Conformer encoder [16] and a 6-block Transformer decoder. Regarding the internal structure, both encoder\nand decoder blocks utilize 4-head self-attention with 256\nhidden units. In particular, the encoder employs macaronstyle blocks equipped with 1024-dimensional feed-forward\nmodules, whereas the decoder blocks incorporate 2048dimensional feed-forward layers.\nIn our experiments, SOT [6], SOT-SACTC [8], and GLADSOT [11] serve as the baseline systems. Additionally, to\nevaluate the efficacy of MoE without global guidance, we implement an SOT + Local MoLE baseline, which incorporates\nlocal Low-Rank experts but relies solely on local routing.\nTo eliminate the influence of model size, we control the\nnumber of encoder layers for each model to ensure parameter\nparity. Accordingly, we assign 14 encoder layers to SOT, 13 to\nSOT-SACTC, and 12 to SOT + Local MoLE, GLAD-SOT, and\nour H-SAGE. As detailed in Table II, this setup guarantees that\nall compared models possess a similar number of parameters.\nFor baseline systems, we adopt the optimal hyperparameters\nreported in their respective papers. For H-SAGE, the MoLE\n\nmodule is configured with 3 experts, setting both the rank\nr and scaling factor α in Eq. 1 to 8, while the OA-Loss\ncoefficient λ in Eq. 4 is set to 3. All models are trained for\n35 epochs. Training is performed on 8 NVIDIA GeForce RTX\n3090 GPUs using the Adam optimizer with a peak learning\nrate of 5e−4 and 25,000 warm-up steps.\nC. Evaluation Metrics\nConsistent with prior studies [7], [8], [11], we evaluate\nsingle-talker performance using Word Error Rate (WER).\nFor multi-talker scenarios, we employ Permutation Invariant\nWER (PI-WER) [6] to resolve speaker permutation ambiguity.\nFurthermore, to provide a fine-grained assessment of robustness, we report Overlap-Aware WER (OA-WER), which is\ncalculated by averaging the WERs across the stratified overlap\nlevels defined previously.\nIt is worth noting that while all models are trained exclusively on single-speaker and 2-speaker data, our evaluation\nextends to 3-speaker mixtures. Specifically, we use the singleand 2-speaker test sets to assess performance on in-domain\nscenarios, whereas the 3-speaker test set is utilized to evaluate the model’s zero-shot generalization capability to unseen\nspeaker numbers.\nV. R ESULTS AND D ISCUSSION\nIn this section, we validate H-SAGE, which demonstrates\nsuperior performance over existing approaches (Tables II\nand III). We provide a detailed analysis covering performance\ncomparisons (Table II), followed by component-wise ablation\nstudies (Table III) verifying the critical role of the proposed\nexplicit modeling and holistic routing mechanisms. Finally,\nwe examine the sensitivity of the auxiliary loss weight λ to\ndetermine the optimal balance for explicit supervision.\nA. Main Results\nIn Table II, we benchmark the proposed H-SAGE (S5)\nagainst representative baselines, analyzing the performance\nevolution across different architectural paradigms.\nPerformance Evolution of Baselines: First, comparing the\nstandard SISO baseline SOT (S1) with SOT + Local MoLE\n(S2), we observe that S2 achieves consistent improvements\ndespite having fewer parameters. This confirms that the effectiveness of S2 stems from the efficient decomposition of diverse acoustic patterns via specialized local experts. Moreover,\nSOT-SACTC [8] (S3) improves performance by introducing an\nexplicit separation constraint. By utilizing speaker-aware CTC,\nS3 guides the encoder to learn disentangled speaker representations in the latent space, proving particularly effective in lowoverlap scenarios. Meanwhile, GLAD-SOT [11] (S4) advances\nthe MoE paradigm of S2. Instead of relying on static local\nexperts, S4 employs a global-local routing mechanism. The\nperformance of S4 demonstrates that for MoE architectures,\ndynamic, context-aware expert selection is as critical as the\nexperts themselves.\nSuperiority of H-SAGE: Building upon these advancements, H-SAGE (S5) addresses the structural limitations of\n\n\fTABLE II: Main performance comparison (WER %) against state-of-the-art baselines on LibriSpeech and LibriSpeechMix\nbenchmarks. Consistent with standard protocols, all models are trained on a unified dataset comprising single-talker and twotalker utterances. The best and second-best results are highlighted in bold underline and underline, respectively.\nLibrispeech\nSystem\n\nMethod\n\nParm.(M)\n\nS1\nS2\nS3\nS4\nS5\n\nSOT [6]\nSOT + Local MoLE\nSOT-SACTC [8]\nGLAD-SOT [11]\nH-SAGE\n\n36.07\n35.09\n35.77\n35.18\n35.75\n\nDev\n\nTest\n\n4.1\n3.7\n3.6\n3.5\n3.6\n\n4.5\n3.8\n3.8\n3.9\n3.8\n\nOverall\nDev\nTest\n8.5\n8.3\n6.4\n6.5\n6.9\n6.7\n6.0\n6.2\n6.0\n5.7\n\nLSM-2mix\nTest(Conditional)\nlow mid high\nOA-WER\n6.2\n8.9\n12.8\n9.3\n5.3\n6.3\n10.3\n7.3\n4.8\n7.2\n10.8\n7.6\n5.1\n6.4\n8.9\n6.8\n4.7\n5.7\n8.2\n6.2\n\nGLAD and achieves the best overall performance. On the\nsingle-speaker LibriSpeech benchmark, H-SAGE maintains\nparity with strong baselines, confirming that the model incurs\nno degradation in clean scenarios. In the two-speaker mixtures\n(LSM-2mix), S5 consistently surpasses all baselines, achieving\nnotable improvements in the challenging mid and high overlap\nconditions. These results suggest that by explicitly modeling\noverlap states, H-SAGE effectively resolves complex feature\nentanglement that hinders previous methods.\nZero-Shot Generalization (LSM-3mix): The advantages\nof H-SAGE are most pronounced in the zero-shot LSM-3mix\nscenario, which evaluates generalization to unseen speaker\ncounts. While baselines struggle to maintain performance,\nH-SAGE maintains a significant lead overall, particularly in\ncomplex high-overlap scenarios. We note a performance gap\nin the LSM-3mix-Low compared to SACTC. This is intuitive:\nSACTC’s explicit separation constraints are highly efficient\nfor sparse, easy-to-separate segments. In contrast, H-SAGE is\noptimized for complex entanglement. Nevertheless, H-SAGE’s\ndominance in the more realistic mid and high overlap scenarios\nvalidates its superior robustness and generalization capability\nwhere it matters most.\nB. Ablation Study\nAs summarized in Tables III, we conduct an ablation study\n(S5–S8) to validate the contributions of core components.\nEffectiveness of Explicit Acoustic Supervision: We compare the full model (S5) against the variant without explicit\nsupervision (S6) to validate the role of LOA . On the clean\nLibrispeech dataset, S5 exhibits a marginal performance drop\ncompared to S6. This can be attributed to the interference\nfrom the auxiliary objective. For clean speech, explicit overlap detection is redundant. Consequently, the auxiliary task\nintroduces optimization noise that marginally degrades S5\ncompared to S6 in the single-speaker scenario.\nHowever, in the in-domain LSM-2mix scenario, S5 surpasses S6. This indicates that explicit supervision effectively\nsharpens the router’s decision boundaries, enabling more precise expert specialization than implicit learning alone. Most\nnotably, S5 achieves substantial gains over S6 in the zeroshot LSM-3mix scenario. This result highlights the critical\nvalue of LOA for generalization. In contrast to S6, which\ntends to overfit to two-speaker patterns, S5 leverages explicit\nsupervision to capture a generic overlap state. This enables\n\nLSM-3mix (zero-shot generalization)\nOverall\nTest(Conditional)\nDev\nTest\nlow\nmid\nhigh OA-WER\n23.8\n24.2\n17.1\n23.8\n32.3\n24.4\n21.1\n21.7\n15.3\n21.6\n28.5\n21.8\n20.6\n20.0\n12.8\n20.0\n27.2\n20.0\n19.9\n19.8\n15.0\n19.5\n25.5\n20.0\n19.7\n19.5\n15.5\n18.9\n24.9\n19.8\n\nTABLE III: Ablation study and architectural analysis on the\nLibriSpeechMix benchmark.\nSystem\n\nMethod\n\nLibrispeech\n\nLSM-2mix\n\nDev\n\nTest\n\nDev\n\nTest\n\nLSM-3mix\n(zero-shot)\nDev\nTest\n\n3.6\n\n3.8\n\n6.0\n\n5.7\n\n19.7\n\n19.5\n\nS6\nS7\nS8\n\nw/o OA-Loss\nw/o SA-Encoder + OA-Loss\nw/o holistic gating\n\n3.5\n3.6\n3.4\n\n3.7\n4.0\n3.9\n\n6.1\n6.2\n6.0\n\n5.8\n6.4\n6.2\n\n20.2\n20.8\n20.4\n\n20.1\n21.5\n20.9\n\nS9\nS10\n\nw MoLE only in FFN\nw MoLE only in Att.\n\n3.9\n3.3\n\n4.2\n3.7\n\n6.8\n6.3\n\n6.4\n6.0\n\n21.2\n20.2\n\n21.3\n20.3\n\nS5\n\nH-SAGE\n\nrobust generalization to unseen scenarios with more speakers,\ndemonstrating the vital role of explicit supervision.\nNecessity of Long-Range Temporal Modeling: To isolate\nthe structural contribution of the global encoder, we compare\nS6 (H-SAGE w/o OA-Loss LOA ) against S7 (H-SAGE w/o\nSA-Encoder). It is important to note that in S7, the absence of\nthe SA-Encoder implies that the global encoder degenerates to\nthe simple frame-independent linear projection used in GLAD.\nThe results show that S6 yields consistent improvements\nover S7 across the majority of metrics. This indicates that even\nwithout explicit supervision, the self-attention structure of SAEncoder inherently captures long-range temporal dependencies\ninaccessible to the linear projection in S7. Unlike the instantaneous mapping in S7, SA-Encoder aggregates information\nacross the sequence, proving that modeling temporal evolution\nof speech is a prerequisite for robust expert assignment.\nNecessity of Holistic Gating Mechanism: We compare HSAGE (S5) with the variant excluding holistic gating (S8).\nNote that in S8, the router degenerates to the GLAD fusion\nmechanism, relying solely on the current layer’s features.\nWe observe comparable performance in the single-speaker\nscenario. This suggests that in clean acoustic environments,\nlocal features provide sufficient guidance. However, H-SAGE\nconsistently outperforms S8 across all other benchmarks,\nincluding in-domain LSM-2mix and zero-shot LSM-3mix scenarios. This confirms that while local cues suffice for simple\ntasks, the holistic view is indispensable for resolving complex\nfeature entanglement in challenging multi-talker environments.\nC. Architectural Analysis\nAs summarized in Table III, we analyze expert placement\nacross the full H-SAGE (S5), the variant with experts applied\nonly to Feed-Forward Networks (FFN) (S9), and the Attentiononly variant (S10). In terms of performance, S5 achieves the\n\n\f6.61\n6.51\n\n6.45\n\nOA-WER\n\nOA-WER\n\n6.7\n6.6\n6.5 6.45\n6.38\n6.4\n6.3\n6.2\n6.1\n0 1\n\n6.2\n\n3\n5\n7\nLambda Value\n\n10\n\n(a) Performance on LSM-2mix\n\n21.0\n20.8\n20.6\n20.4 20.24\n20.2 20.02\n20.0\n19.8\n19.6\n19.4\n0 1\n\n20.78\n20.56\n\n20.02\n19.78\n\n3\n5\n7\nLambda Value\n\n10\n\n(b) Performance on LSM-3mix\n\nFig. 3: Impact of the auxiliary loss weight λ on OA-WER\nperformance.\nbest results, followed by S10, with S9 trailing. This ranking\nconfirms that deploying experts in both modules yields a\nsynergistic effect, maximizing the capacity to handle complex\nacoustic variations.\nNotably, our analysis reveals a correlation between global\nmodeling strength and optimal expert placement. In prior\nMoE-based MTASR studies, although attention experts are\noften regarded as crucial, FFN experts can outperform them in\ncertain scenarios due to stronger feature transformation capabilities. However, the introduction of the SA-Encoder enhances\nthe effectiveness of attention experts. Our experiments show\nS10 consistently outperforms S9, indicating that when global\nfeatures are robustly captured, expert specialization within the\nattention mechanism becomes pivotal. Inherently designed for\nsequence modeling, the attention mechanism is structurally\ncompatible with global cues from the SA-Encoder. This allows\nit to effectively utilize these cues for speaker disentanglement.\nThus, while FFN experts provide limited support in certain\nscenarios, attention-based experts become more critical once\nthe acoustic state is effectively modeled.\nD. Impact of Auxiliary Loss Weight λ\nWe evaluate the auxiliary weight λ in Eq. 4 across the set\n{0, 1, 3, 5, 7, 10}. As illustrated in Fig. 3, we observe that λ =\n3 consistently yields optimal performance for both in-domain\n(LSM-2mix) and zero-shot (LSM-3mix) scenarios. Notably,\nwhile the trend in the simpler 2-mix scenario shows slight\nfluctuations, the more challenging 3-mix scenario exhibits a\ndistinct U-shaped pattern. This indicates that while the model\nhandles in-domain data relatively easily, explicit supervision\nof speaker activity states becomes critical for generalizing\nto complex, unseen acoustic environments. However, further\nincreasing λ beyond 3 leads to degradation in both cases, as an\noverly dominant auxiliary objective overshadows the primary\ntranscription task. Consequently, we set λ = 3 to balance\noverlap awareness and ASR accuracy.\nVI. C ONCLUSION\nIn this paper, we propose Holistic Speaker-Aware Guided\nExperts (H-SAGE), a framework that shifts MoE-based\nMTASR from implicit adaptation to explicit acoustic modeling. By integrating a Speaker-Aware Global Encoder with\na Holistic Gating Mechanism, H-SAGE captures dynamic\nspeaker states and improves expert selection. Experiments\n\non LibriSpeechMix show that H-SAGE outperforms stateof-the-art methods, especially under high-overlap conditions.\nFurthermore, ablation analyses confirm that explicit acoustic\nsupervision and a holistic view are indispensable for disentangling speakers in complex environments.\nR EFERENCES\n[1] Xinlu He and Jacob Whitehill, “Survey of end-to-end multi-speaker\nautomatic speech recognition for monaural audio,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2505.10975, 2025.\n[2] Dong Yu, Xuankai Chang, and Yanmin Qian, “Recognizing multitalker speech with permutation invariant training,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:1704.01985, 2017.\n[3] Shane Settle, Jonathan Le Roux, Takaaki Hori, Shinji Watanabe, and\nJohn R Hershey, “End-to-end multi-speaker speech recognition,” in\n2018 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal\nprocessing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2018, pp. 4819–4823.\n[4] Xuankai Chang, Wangyou Zhang, Yanmin Qian, Jonathan Le Roux, and\nShinji Watanabe, “End-to-end multi-speaker speech recognition with\ntransformer,” in ICASSP 2020-2020 IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2020, pp.\n6134–6138.\n[5] Dong Yu, Morten Kolbæk, Zheng-Hua Tan, and Jesper Jensen, “Permutation invariant training of deep models for speaker-independent multitalker speech separation,” in 2017 IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2017, pp.\n241–245.\n[6] Naoyuki Kanda, Yashesh Gaur, Xiaofei Wang, Zhong Meng, and Takuya\nYoshioka, “Serialized output training for end-to-end overlapped speech\nrecognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2003.12687, 2020.\n[7] Jiawen Kang, Lingwei Meng, Mingyu Cui, Haohan Guo, Xixin Wu,\nXunying Liu, and Helen Meng, “Cross-speaker encoding network\nfor multi-talker speech recognition,” in ICASSP 2024-2024 IEEE\nInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP). IEEE, 2024, pp. 11986–11990.\n[8] Jiawen Kang, Lingwei Meng, Mingyu Cui, Yuejiao Wang, Xixin Wu,\nXunying Liu, and Helen Meng, “Disentangling speakers in multi-talker\nspeech recognition with speaker-aware ctc,” in ICASSP 2025-2025 IEEE\nInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP). IEEE, 2025, pp. 1–5.\n[9] Asahi Sakuma, Hiroaki Sato, Ryuga Sugano, Tadashi Kumano, Yoshihiko Kawai, and Tetsuji Ogawa, “Speaker-distinguishable ctc: Learning\nspeaker distinction using ctc for multi-talker speech recognition,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2506.07515, 2025.\n[10] Weiqing Wang, Taejin Park, Ivan Medennikov, Jinhan Wang, Kunal\nDhawan, He Huang, Nithin Rao Koluguri, Jagadeesh Balam, and Boris\nGinsburg, “Speaker targeting via self-speaker adaptation for multi-talker\nasr,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2506.22646, 2025.\n[11] Yujie Guo, Jiaming Zhou, Yuhang Jia, Shiwan Zhao, and Yong Qin,\n“Glad: Global-local aware dynamic mixture-of-experts for multi-talker\nasr,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2509.13093, 2025.\n[12] Chongyang Gao, Kezhen Chen, Jinmeng Rao, Ruibo Liu, Baochen\nSun, Yawen Zhang, Daiyi Peng, Xiaoyuan Guo, and VS Subrahmanian,\n“Mola: Moe lora with layer-wise expert allocation,” in Findings of\nthe Association for Computational Linguistics: NAACL 2025, 2025, pp.\n5097–5112.\n[13] Edward J Hu, Yelong Shen, Phillip Wallis, Zeyuan Allen-Zhu, Yuanzhi\nLi, Shean Wang, Lu Wang, Weizhu Chen, et al., “Lora: Low-rank\nadaptation of large language models.,” ICLR, vol. 1, no. 2, pp. 3, 2022.\n[14] Vassil Panayotov, Guoguo Chen, Daniel Povey, and Sanjeev Khudanpur,\n“Librispeech: an asr corpus based on public domain audio books,” in\n2015 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal\nprocessing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n[15] Shinji Watanabe, Takaaki Hori, Shigeki Karita, Tomoki Hayashi, Jiro\nNishitoba, Yuya Unno, Nelson Enrique Yalta Soplin, Jahn Heymann,\nMatthew Wiesner, Nanxin Chen, Adithya Renduchintala, and Tsubasa\nOchiai, “ESPnet: End-to-end speech processing toolkit,” in Proceedings\nof Interspeech, 2018, pp. 2207–2211.\n[16] Anmol Gulati, James Qin, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Niki Parmar, Yu Zhang,\nJiahui Yu, Wei Han, Shibo Wang, Zhengdong Zhang, Yonghui Wu,\net al., “Conformer: Convolution-augmented transformer for speech\nrecognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2005.08100, 2020.\n\n\f", "numLines": 963, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 963}}}
